<TEXT>
declaring that he has an unfinished 
agenda us sen mark hatfield said saturday night that he would 
run for a fifth term 
the announcement by the oregon republican ended months of 
speculation about the plans of the states most popular politician 
ive come to the conclusion that ours is an unfinished 
agenda hatfield said told about 350 supporters 
hatfield said he played a key role in fashioning the recent 
congressional compromise on harvest of old growth timber 
environmentalists had initally opposed harvesting any virgin timber 
on federal land the compromise allows some logging 
i will not rest until we have secured a longterm solution to 
our timber supply problems hatfield said 
hatfield 67 also said that if reelected he would work to 
provide better health care to oregonians to step up the fight 
against drugs and to slow the nuclear arms race 
following a longstanding tradition hatfield made the 
announcement in silverton where hes launched all of his previous 
campaigns 
friends and political supporters of hatfield including 
president bush had encouraged the senator to run again 
gov neil goldschmidt a democrat also asked him to run again 
hatfield won a seat in the oregon house in 1950 and was elected 
secretary of state in 1956 after two terms as governor he was 
elected to the us senate in 1966 
a formal naval officer who was one of the first americans to 
witness firsthand the aftermath of the atomic bombing of hiroshima 
hatfield earned a reputation as a staunch foe of the vietnam war 
